natural problem:
The values of a function $f(x)$ are given below:

\begin{tabular}{|c||c|c|c|c|c|} \hline $x$ & 3 & 4 & 5 & 6 & 7 \\ \hline $f(x)$ & 10 & 17 & 26 & 37 & 50 \\ \hline \end{tabular}Evaluate $f^{-1}\left(f^{-1}(50)\times f^{-1}(10)+f^{-1}(26)\right)$.

a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes f :: "int \<Rightarrow> int"
assumes h0 : "bij f"
and h1 : "\<forall>x. (x = 3 \<longrightarrow> f x = 10) \<and> (x = 4 \<longrightarrow> f x = 17) \<and> (x = 5 \<longrightarrow> f x = 26) \<and> (x = 6 \<longrightarrow> f x = 37) \<and> (x = 7 \<longrightarrow> f x = 50)"
and h2 : "f (inv f (inv f 50) * inv f 10 + inv f 26) = 5"
shows  "f 5 = 5"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 The values of a function $f(x)$ are given below:

\begin{tabular}{|c||c|c|c|c|c|} \hline $x$ & 3 & 4 & 5 & 6 & 7 \\ \hline $f(x)$ & 10 & 17 & 26 & 37 & 50 \\ \hline \end{tabular}Evaluate $f^{-1}\left(f^{-1}(50)\times f^{-1}(10)+f^{-1}(26)\right)$. The final Answer is 5
 ### Proof
 Since $f(7)=50$, we have $f^{-1}(50)=7$.
 Similarly, $f(3)=10$ and $f(5)=26$, so $f^{-1}(10)=3$ and $f^{-1}(26)=5$.
 Therefore,  \begin{align}f^{-1}\left(f^{-1}(50)\times f^{-1}(10)+f^{-1}(26)\right)&=f^{-1}(7\times3+5)\\ &=f^{-1}(26)=\boxed{5}.\end{align}
 *)

theorem
fixes f :: "int \<Rightarrow> int"
assumes h0 : "bij f"
and h1 : "\<forall>x. (x = 3 \<longrightarrow> f x = 10) \<and> (x = 4 \<longrightarrow> f x = 17) \<and> (x = 5 \<longrightarrow> f x = 26) \<and> (x = 6 \<longrightarrow> f x = 37) \<and> (x = 7 \<longrightarrow> f x = 50)"
and h2 : "f (inv f (inv f 50) * inv f 10 + inv f 26) = 5"
shows  "f 5 = 5"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer
a_0.informal problem: Assume a function $f$ is a bijection. Given that $f(3)=10$, $f(4)=17$, $f(5)=26$, $f(6)=37$ and $f(7)=50$, find the value of $f$ such that $f((f^{-1}(f^{-1}(50)) * f^{-1}(10)) + f^{-1}(26)) = 5$. The final answer is $f(5) = 5$.
